I'm using the weighted average of the past and current season winrate to determine the probability distribution for the number of wins at the end of the season using Poisson. Then I'm taking random values from such distribution and simulating 500 seasons to determine the likelihood of each team to win the division.
The Seahawks surprised while everyone else disappointed.

My initial forecast comes purely from a base rate estimation. I started by analyzing the probability distribution of winrate change from one year to the next and found that 2/3 of the times each team remains within +/- 20% of the winrate of the previous year.

The Rams are defending Super Bowl champions and all of their best players are returning. They possess the best wide receiver, cornerback, and defensive tackle in the league with Cooper Kupp, Jalen Ramsey, and Aaron Donald. Quarterback Matthew Stafford and Head Coach Sean McVay have now proven themselves and should no longer be doubted. The addition of stud receiver Allen Robinson II, who has looked stellar in preseason, ensures the Rams will be very likely to win the division. Although the 49ers are coming off an NFC championship appearance, the uncertainty with second year QB Trey Lance means they will be a hit or a flop this season. The Cardinals are an enigma, but with stars like JJ Watt, Kyler Murray, and Deandre Hopkins, it is hard to write them off. The Seahawks are in contention for the no. 1 pick in next year's draft, having the league's worst starting quarterback and the division's worst roster
The rams are the outright favorites and it is pretty likely they will win
